00:00:00.460 --> 00:00:03.540
What I want to do in this video
is establish a reasonably

00:00:03.540 --> 00:00:07.540
powerful condition in which we
can establish that at vector

00:00:07.540 --> 00:00:10.350
field, or that a line integral
of a vector field is

00:00:10.350 --> 00:00:11.670
path independent.

00:00:11.670 --> 00:00:14.420
And when I say that, I mean
that let's say I were to take

00:00:14.420 --> 00:00:21.780
this line integral along the
path c of f dot d r, and let's

00:00:21.780 --> 00:00:24.310
say my path looks like this.

00:00:28.110 --> 00:00:34.020
That's my x and y axis, and
let's say my path looks

00:00:34.020 --> 00:00:37.530
something like this: I start
there and I go over

00:00:37.530 --> 00:00:40.510
there to point c.

00:00:40.510 --> 00:00:43.050
My end point, the
curve here is c.

00:00:43.050 --> 00:00:46.210
And so I would evaluate this
line integral, this victor

00:00:46.210 --> 00:00:48.640
field along this path.

00:00:48.640 --> 00:00:52.420
This would be a path
independent vector field, or we

00:00:52.420 --> 00:00:59.890
call that a conservative vector
field, if this thing is equal

00:00:59.890 --> 00:01:06.370
to the same integral over a
different path that has

00:01:06.370 --> 00:01:07.240
the same end point.

00:01:07.240 --> 00:01:11.250
So let's call this c1, so
this is c1, and this is c2.

00:01:11.250 --> 00:01:15.680
This vector field is
conservative if I start

00:01:15.680 --> 00:01:17.530
at the same point but I
take a different path.

00:01:17.530 --> 00:01:22.050
Let's say I go something like
that: if I take a different

00:01:22.050 --> 00:01:27.600
path-- and this is my c2 --I
still get the same value.

00:01:27.600 --> 00:01:30.190
What this is telling me is that
all it cares about to evaluate

00:01:30.190 --> 00:01:33.980
these integrals is my starting
point and my ending point.

00:01:33.980 --> 00:01:35.750
It doesn't care what
I do in between.

00:01:35.750 --> 00:01:38.410
It doesn't care how I get
from my starting point

00:01:38.410 --> 00:01:40.140
to my end point.

00:01:40.140 --> 00:01:42.610
These two integrals have the
same start point and same end

00:01:42.610 --> 00:01:45.320
point, so irregardless of
their actual path, they're

00:01:45.320 --> 00:01:46.350
going to be the same.

00:01:46.350 --> 00:01:50.530
That's what it means for f to
be a conservative field, or

00:01:50.530 --> 00:01:54.670
what it means for this integral
to be path independent.

00:01:54.670 --> 00:01:58.080
So before I prove or I show you
