00:15:39.180 --> 00:15:43.150
call it, and we found that we
can evaluate this integral by

00:15:43.150 --> 00:15:47.170
evaluating capital F at t is
equal to b, and then

00:15:47.170 --> 00:15:50.570
subtracting from that capital
F at t is equal to a.

00:15:50.570 --> 00:15:52.860
But what that tells you is that
this integral, the value of

00:15:52.860 --> 00:15:58.980
this integral, is only
dependent at our starting

00:15:58.980 --> 00:16:06.090
point, t is equal to a, this is
the point x of a, y of a, and

00:16:06.090 --> 00:16:13.810
the ending point, t is equal to
b, which is x of b, y of b.

00:16:13.810 --> 00:16:16.020
That integral is only dependent
on these two values.

00:16:16.020 --> 00:16:17.300
How do I know that?

00:16:17.300 --> 00:16:20.340
Because to solve it-- because
I'm saying that this thing

00:16:20.340 --> 00:16:23.880
exists --I just had to evaluate
that thing at those two

00:16:23.880 --> 00:16:26.890
points; I didn't care about
the curve in between.

00:16:26.890 --> 00:16:34.450
So this shows that if F is
equal to the gradient-- this

00:16:34.450 --> 00:16:37.340
is often called a potential
function of capital F, although

00:16:37.340 --> 00:16:39.590
they're usually the negative
each other, but it's the same

00:16:39.590 --> 00:16:44.220
idea --if the vector field f is
the gradient of some scale or

00:16:44.220 --> 00:16:56.490
field upper-case F, then we can
say that f is conservative or

00:16:56.490 --> 00:17:00.980
that the line integral of f
dot dr is path independent.

00:17:00.980 --> 00:17:04.420
It doesn't matter what path we
go on as long as our starting

00:17:04.420 --> 00:17:06.420
and ending point are the same.

00:17:06.420 --> 00:17:07.580
Hopefully found that useful.

00:17:07.580 --> 00:17:08.680
And we'll some
examples with that.

00:17:08.680 --> 00:17:10.990
